A B S T R A C T
Neurotransmitters, including 5-hydroxytryptamine (5-HT), dopamine (DA), gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA),
and glutamate, are essential transductors in the Gut-Brain Axis (GBA), playing critical roles both peripherally and
centrally. Accumulating evidence suggests that the gut microbiota modulates intestinal neurotransmitter meta-
bolism and gut-to-brain signaling, shedding light on the crucial role of the gut microbiota in brain function and
the pathogenesis of various neuropsychiatric diseases, such as major depression disorder (MDD), anxiety,
addiction and Parkinson’s disease (PD). Despite the exciting findings, the mechanisms underlying the modulation
of neurotransmitter metabolism and function by the gut microbiota are still being elucidated. In this review, we
aim to provide a comprehensive overview of the existing knowledge about the role of the gut microbiota in
neurotransmitter metabolism and function in animal and clinical experiments. Moreover, we will discuss the
potential mechanisms through which gut microbiota-derived neurotransmitters contribute to the pathogenesis of
neuropsychiatric diseases, thus highlighting a novel therapeutic target for these conditions.
1. Introduction
The gut microbiota influences the metabolism and function of
various neurotransmitters, including dopamine (DA), serotonin (5-HT),
glutamate, and γ-aminobutyric acid (GABA), thereby affecting gut-brain
signaling, a process we refer to as the gut-brain axis (GBA). The mech-
anisms by which the gut microbiota regulates neurotransmitters in the
gut and brain are not yet fully understood. Current literature suggests
these mechanisms may include direct involvement in the synthesis of
neurotransmitters, influencing rate-limiting enzymes in key metabolic
reactions, or impacting the transporters of certain neurotransmitters.
The gut microbiota can also alter the expression of specific receptor
subtypes in the enteric nervous system (ENS), such as the 5-HT3 receptor
(BHATTARAI et al., 2017) and 5-HT4 receptor (DE VADDER et al.,
2018a), and then activate the vagus nervous system (VNS), thereby
affecting neurotransmitter levels in the brain.
Notably, a focal point of investigation is how neurotransmitter
changes within the gut lumen impact the central nervous system (CNS)
via the blood-brain barrier (BBB). By categorizing the various neuro-
transmitters, we aim to provide a more comprehensive overview of how
gut microbiota-mediated amino acid metabolism influences neuro-
transmitter levels. Furthermore, we summarize the potential of pro-
biotics in the treatment of psychiatric disorders, given the association
between brain neurotransmitter levels and the occurrence of these
disorders.
Finally, while the ENS and gut epithelial barrier are often overlooked
in gut-brain signaling, they play significant roles in microbial trans-
location and the brain’s perception of gut luminal signals. Thus, we also
discuss recent research advancements regarding the gut epithelial bar-
rier, highlighting its crucial role in gut-brain signal transduction and
brain function. Although the role of specific microbial populations in the
pathogenesis of psychiatric disorders is not yet fully elucidated, we aim
to systematically present the intricate connections between the gut
microbiota, ENS, vagus nerve, and CNS. This review seeks to inspire
further research on the GBA and its implications for psychiatric
disorders.
