2. Gut microbiota modulates 5-HT and gut-brain signaling
5-HT, also known as serotonin, is widely distributed throughout both
the central and peripheral nervous systems of humans. While only
approximately 5 % of serotonin is produced in the brain, the remaining
95 % is primarily synthesized in the gut (ERSPAMER, 1954). In the CNS,
5-HT is an essential neurotransmitter to regulate mood, sleep, and
appetite (BERGER et al., 2009). In contrast, in the gut, most of the 5-HT
is released from enterochromaffin cells (ECCs), a subtype of enter-
oendocrine cells (EECs), forming direct connections with ENS endings
innervating the gut (PAN and GERSHON, 2000). Central 5-HT plays a
crucial role in inducing the maturation of the adult ENS (DE VADDER
et al., 2018b) and contributes to the regulation of motility and secretion
of intestinal fluids (TECOTT, 2007).
Both in CNS and ENS, 5-HT is produced through the serotonin
pathway from tryptophan (TRP). While the kynurenine pathway me-
tabolizes more than 95 % of TRP, only about 1 % enters the serotonin
pathway. In the serotonin pathway (CLARKE et al., 2013), TRP un-
dergoes initial metabolism to form 5-hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP), sub-
sequently metabolized by tryptophan hydroxylase (TPH) and aromatic
amino acid decarboxylase. Both TRP and 5-HTP can cross BBB via amino
acid transporters and participate in 5-HT synthesis of the CNS. TPH is
the first rate-limiting enzyme in the serotonin pathway, and it exists in
two isoforms: TPH1, which is mainly present in the periphery tissues
(such as the gastrointestinal tract and skin), and TPH2, which exists in
neuronal cells. TPH1 predominantly regulates the level of circulating
5-HT. In the serotonin pathway, 5-HT is further metabolized by mono-
amine oxidase (MAO) to form 5-hydroxy indole acetic acid. In the
kynurenine pathway (YANO et al., 2015), TRP is initially converted to
N-formyl-kynurenine by tryptophan 2,3-dioxygenase (TDO) and indo-
leamine 2,3-dioxygenase (IDO), subsequently transformed to kynur-
enine (KYN) by formamidase. Additionally, KYN can undergo further
metabolism to produce to kynurenic acid and quinolinic acid. The
KYN/TRP ratio is commonly used to evaluate the activity of the
kynurenine pathway (SORGDRAGER et al., 2019). Kynurenic acid is
known to provide neuroprotection against excitotoxicity induced by
quinolinic acid (VENKATESAN et al., 2020), and its levels can influence
the
extracellular
concentrations
of
glutamate,
DA,
and
GABA
(RAMOS-CH´aVEZ et al., 2018). There may be several mechanisms by
which the microbiota influences the level of 5-HT in the gut and brain.
2.1. Gut microbiota promotes the serotonin pathway
The gut microbiota has been shown to directly or indirectly influence
the level of TPH1 in the gut, which in turn activates the serotonin
pathway in ECCs, ultimately affecting the level of TPH2 in the brain
(Fig. 1A a). Studies have demonstrated that microbiota derived from
humans and mice can promote the production of TPH1 and serotonin in
the gut by stimulating the activities of short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs)
such as butyrate and acetate on ECCs (REIGSTAD et al., 2015). For
example, Clostridium ramosum leads to an increase in gut 5-HT by
leading to a significant increase in Tph1 expression (MANDI´C et al.,
2019).
Experimental evidence suggests that certain probiotics, including
Lactobacillus rhamnosus and Bifidobacterium longum, can increase the
levels of TPH2 and serotonin while decreasing the level of IDO in the
frontal cortex, exerting anti-depressive effects in rats (LI et al., 2019).
Consumption of Lactobacillus plantarum DR7 for 12 weeks can reduce
anxiety symptoms and total psychological scores in stressed adults
(CHONG et al., 2019). The gut microbiota can play a protective role
during the early development of the intestinal mucosa and, through the
5-HT4 receptor, promote the generation of enteric neurons (DE VADDER
et al., 2018a). These findings suggest that targeting the serotonin
pathway through the gut microbiota could hold significant promise in
treating diseases associated with 5-HT dysfunction.
2.2. Gut microbiota suppresses the kynurenine pathway
The gut microbiota promotes 5-HT production in the gut by sup-
pressing the production of KYN (Fig. 1A b). A mouse experiment showed
that chronic restraint stress decreased the level of TPH2 and increased
IDO1 in mice with depression and anxiety-like behavior. And a negative
correlation with Enterorhabdus, Parabacteroides in the gut, and KYN
levels in the brain was observed (DENG et al., 2021). Gut microbiota can
influence the key enzymes in the Kynurenine pathway, especially IDO1.
For instance, Clostridium(MARTIN-GALLAUSIAUX et al., 2018) can
produce SCFAs to inhibit IDO1 expression and reduce KYN levels in
blood circulation. Gut microbiota could get an excellent therapeutic
effect when used for treatment. Multi-strain probiotic formulation
restored
the
plasma
levels
of
L-tryptophan,
L-kynurenine,
kynurenic-acid, and 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, reversing the decreased
BDNF level in the hippocampus and frontal cortex (LI et al., 2019). An
animal experiment (XIE et al., 2020) demonstrated that treatment with
Lactobacillus reuteri 3 ameliorated depressive-like behaviors, increased
the level of enzymes involved in the 5-HT pathway, and suppressed
metabolic products in the kynurenine pathway like IDO1 in the colon
and prefrontal cortex. Clinical trials also showed a correlation between
microbes and the kynurenine pathway in patients with depression. The
relative abundance of Actinomycetes increased while the plasma TRP and
the Kynurenine pathway decreased in MDD patients compared with
healthy control (LAI et al., 2021). Treatment based on gut microbiota
has brought new ideas to the adjuvant treatment of depression. A clin-
ical trial has demonstrated that combining selective serotonin reuptake
inhibitors (SSRIs) with the probiotic bacteria Lactobacillus plantarum
299 v can lower KYN levels and increase the 3-hydroxykynurenine
(3HKYN) to KYN ratio, indicating enhanced kynurenine 3-monooxyge-
nase (KMO) activity. This combination treatment has shown promise
in improving cognitive performance in depressed patients compared to
SSRIs alone with a placebo probiotic (RUDZKI et al., 2019). In addition,
using probiotics alone also has a good effect. A clinical experiment
(KAZEMI et al., 2019) showed that probiotic supplementation contain-
ing Lactobacillus helveticus and Bifidobacterium longum significantly
reduced Beck Depression Inventory scores with the decreased ratio of
circulation KYN/TRP in patients with MDD. And Bifidobacterium breve
CCFM1025 was shown to be effective in the treatment of MDD in
four-week clinical trials due to changes in intestinal tryptophan meta-
bolism (TIAN et al., 2022). So gut microbiota that targets Kynurenine
pathway, promotes the 5-HT production indirectly, and could also be
potential therapeutic targets (MITREA et al., 2022).
2.3. Gut microbiota themselves can produce and reuptake 5-HT
Several bacterial strains like Lactic acid bacteria and Escherichia coli
that can directly produce 5-HT have also been reported (Table 1, Fig. 1A
c). Moreover, some strains express proteins that are homologous to the
mammalian serotonin transporter (SERT). SERT is a protein responsible
for the reuptake of serotonin from the synaptic cleft back into the pre-
synaptic neuron. This process is essential for the termination of seroto-
nin signaling and the regulation of serotonin levels in the brain. For
instance, Fung reported that Turicibacter sanguinis expresses a protein
that facilitates 5-HT uptake via a mechanism that can be blocked by
SSRIs. This action elevates levels of intestinal lumenal 5-HT and in-
creases the relative abundance of spore-forming members of the gut
microbiota, which were previously reported to promote host 5-HT
biosynthesis (FUNG et al., 2019). SSRIs may interact synergistically
with other drugs that affect different microbial strains, potentially
leading to dysbiosis of the gut microbiota. This interaction could influ-
ence the therapeutic efficacy in patients who are on long-term SSRI
treatment (SJ¨oSTEDT et al., 2021).
