2.4. Gut microbiota affects the intestinal expression of SERT
The gut microbiota can also modulate the level of 5-HT by influ-
encing the expression of SERT in their host (Fig. 1A d). Upregulation of
SERT expression, accompanied by reduced 5-HT levels, has been
observed in colonic tissue of mice receiving feces from patients with
constipation and decreased Clostridium and Lactobacillus abundance, as
well as increased Bacteroides and Akkermansia abundance (CAO et al.,
2017). Transplantation of fecal flora in children with autism to mice
showed low SERT and 5-HT receptors and high TPH1 expression levels
in the colon (XIAO et al., 2021). Reports have confirmed that Bifido-
bacterium dentium (ENGEVIK et al., 2021), Lactobacillus plantarum
PS128 (CHEN et al., 2022), and others (Table 1) can upregulate the
expression of SERT. Additionally, Akkermansia muciniphila and Faecali-
bacterium prausnitzii have been shown to increase SERT expression in
human epithelial colorectal adenocarcinoma cell culture (YAGHOUB-
FAR et al., 2021) and colon of mice (YAGHOUBFAR et al., 2020). Our
data showed that long-term administration of Akkermansia muciniphila
in mice could significantly suppress the SERT expression in intestinal
tissue, corresponding to the increase of 5-HT in both the gut and brain
(GUO et al., 2024).
2.5. Gut microbiota influences the intestinal expression of 5-HT Receptors
The gut microbiota can influence the expression of gut 5-HT re-
ceptors, which might further impact the 5-HT gut-brain signaling
(Fig. 1C e). For instance, human-derived microbiota can decrease in-
testinal secretion in mice colon by producing acetate and decreasing the
expression of intestinal 5-HT3 receptors (BHATTARAI et al., 2017).
Akkermansia muciniphila has been found to increase the expression of the
5-HT4 receptor gene in the gut while decreasing the expression of the
5-HT2B, 5-HT3B, and 5-HT7 receptors (YAGHOUBFAR et al., 2020).
Lactobacillus plantarum PS128 has been shown to increase the level of
TPH1 and 5-HT in the gut while decreasing the expression of SERT and
5-HT4 receptors (CHEN et al., 2022). In mice with gastrointestinal (GI)
motility disorders, the expression of THP1 and 5-HT4R increased and the
expression of SERT decreased indicating that they were improved by
intervention in the group with L. paracasei JY062 and L. gasseri JM1
(CHENG et al., 2023).. In clinical trials, drugs targeting 5-HT4 receptors
are commonly utilized to treat irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) patients,
and microbiota that target these receptors may offer a complementary
therapy (FUKUDO et al., 2021) (HAMATANI et al., 2020). Furthermore,
these effects may also extend to the expression of 5-HT receptors in the
brain. Mice colonized B.dentium led to an increase in fecal acetate levels,
which corresponded to an up-regulation of intestinal 5-HT and increased
expression of 5-HT2A, 5-HT4 receptors, SERT, and hippocampal 5-HT2A
receptors, accompanied by the reverse of anxiety-like behaviors
(ENGEVIK et al., 2021). Therefore, it may be possible to increase the
responsiveness of patients to 5-HT by up-regulating the 5-HT receptors
of the CNS through microbiota in future clinical treatment.
These findings suggest that modulation of the gut microbiota could
potentially increase the responsiveness of patients to 5-HT by up-
regulating 5-HT receptors in the CNS, offering novel therapeutic ap-
proaches for brain disorders.
2.6. Gut Microbiota Influenced by 5-HT Metabolic Pathways
The 5-HT metabolic pathways can also influence the microbiota in
turn. For example, compared to the Tph1+/- mice, 5 operational taxo-
nomic units (OTUs) within the Bacteroidetes, 2 taxa in the Firmicutes, and
1 Proteobacteria OTU in Tph1-/- mice were increased (KWON et al.,
2019). Sert-/- mice displayed a higher abundance of Bacilli species and a
