3. Gut microbiota modulates DA and gut-brain signaling
DA plays a crucial role in both CNS and peripheral nervous systems
(MISSALE et al., 1998). In the CNS, DA is related to learning, motivation
(MOHEBI et al., 2019), pain modulation (HUANG et al., 2020) and brain
reward functions (KALMBACH et al., 2022). DA abnormalities can lead
to PD. (SACKNER-BERNSTEIN, 2021), autism spectrum disorder (ASD)
(LIU et al., 2017), and schizophrenia disease (RINC´oN-CORT´eS and
GRACE, 2022), influencing feeding and addictive behaviors. In the gut,
DA helps protect the GI mucosa, regulating GI motility, secretion, ab-
sorption, and other physiological functions by binding with DA re-
ceptors and/or adrenergic receptors (FURNESS, 2012).
The synthesis of DA occurs through the phenylalanine-tyrosine-
dopa-dopamine pathway, which can take place both in the gut and
brain. Phenylalanine, an essential amino acid, is converted into tyrosine
in the kidney, which then enters circulation. Tyrosine is further con-
verted into levodopa (L-DOPA) by the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase
(TH), a rate-limiting step in DA synthesis and a marker for assessing
levels (VAN KESSEL et al., 2019a). Tyrosine and L-DOPA can enter the
brain through BBB, but L-DOPA is rapidly converted to DA by dopa
decarboxylase in the small intestine due to its instability. There are
several mechanisms by which gut microbiota affects host DA levels.
3.1. Gut microbiota regulates levodopa metabolic processes
The gut microbiota can influence the host L-DOPA and DA produc-
tion. Research indicates that broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy reduces
levels of Firmicutes while increasing levels of Proteobacteria, Verrucomi-
crobia, Bacteroidetes, and Cyanobacteria. This therapy also elevated
striatal IL-1β and TNF-α, which protected dopaminergic neurons, pre-
vented TH reduction and alleviated motor deficits in rodent models of
PD (PU et al., 2019; KOUTZOUMIS et al., 2020). A reduced relative
abundance
of
Lactobacillus
and
Bacteroides
was
found
in
rotenone-treated mice with loss of TH neurons in the substantial nigra
(BHATTARAI et al., 2021). Treating PD mice with the probiotic Clos-
tridium increased the relative abundance of Akkermansia, Enterorhabdus,
and Helicobacter, preventing the reduction of TH (+) dopaminergic
neurons. Also, in MPTP (1-methyl-4-phenyl-1,2,3,6-tetrahydropyridine,
a neurotoxin that selectively damages dopaminergic neurons)-induced
mice, Clostridium can improve motor defects, synaptic dysfunction,
and microglial cell activation (WANG et al., 2022).
In PD patients, the abundance of Actinobacteria, Proteus, and Warts
significantly increases, while Bacteroides and Firmicutes decrease,
accompanied by an increase in phenylalanine levels (VASCELLARI et al.,
2020). Clinical trials administering Lactobacillus plantarum PS128 along
with L-DOPA or other anti-parkinsonian drugs decreased inflammation
levels, thus improving motor symptoms and quality of life (LU et al.,
2021). These findings suggest that the gut microbiota not only regulates
DA levels but also plays an essential role in DA production.
3.2. Gut microbiota themselves can produce DA
The gut symbiont Clostridium sporogenes produces phenylalanine
(DODD et al., 2017). Also, Bifidobacterium dentium can synthesize tyro-
sine from phenylalanine in the gut (LUCK et al., 2021). A study found
that oral berberine can promote the synthesis of L-DOPA and DA in the
gut
by
activating
the
TH
and
dopa
decarboxylase
in
dopamine-synthesizing bacteria, such as E. faecalis and E. faecium,
leading to increased DA levels in the brain (WANG et al., 2021). The
tyrosine decarboxylase in some gut microbiota can convert L-DOPA to
DA (ZOETENDAL et al., 2012) (Table 1). High abundance of intestinal
bacteria with tyrosine decarboxylase activity in PD patients can reduce
levodopa levels in the gut. The relative abundance of these bacteria is
higher in the proximal small intestine, the primary absorption site of
L-DOPA (VAN KESSEL et al., 2019a). Additionally, an inverse correla-
tion exists between the presence of bacterial species with tyrosine
decarboxylase activity and levodopa levels in systemic circulation,
potentially affecting L-DOPA bioavailability (VAN KESSEL et al., 2022).
3.3. Gut Microbiota Affects the Expression of DA Transporters
The gut microbiota can affect host DA transporters (DAT), a protein
responsible for DA reuptake and clearance of synaptic space in the brain.
Studies have shown that an increase in fecal levels of uniform Bacter-
oides is significantly correlated with an increase in DAT, while an in-
crease in Prevotella genus is negatively correlated (HARTSTRA et al.,
2020). The antibiotic cocktail treatment prevented the DAT loss and
protected against MPTP-induced dopaminergic neurotoxicity in the
mice models (PU et al., 2019). Other evidence indicates that psycho-
biotics containing Lactobacillus plantarum PS128 enhanced dopamine
metabolism in the striatum and prefrontal cortex, increased DAT, and
improved DA-related neurological disorders (LIAO et al., 2019). Lacto-
bacillus plantarum PS128 and its fermentation products could inhibit
several depression-related bacteria, such as P. aeruginosa, S. epidermidis,
K. pneumonia, and S. aureus (LIAO et al., 2019) which provides new ideas
for depression treatment.
Influencing DAT through gut microbiota may also affect addictive
behaviors. Drugs such as cocaine and amphetamine inhibit DAT, in-
crease extracellular DA levels, and thus act on the midbrain cortical
hormone system, influencing the development and expression of
addictive behaviors caused by sustained drug-induced neural adaptation
in the midbrain cortical neural circuit (GONZ´aLEZ-ARANCIBIA et al.,
2019). Lactobacillus administration can increase the level of DAT,
thereby treating alcohol addiction (EZQUER et al., 2022). The use of
antibiotics to modify gut microbiota can also particularly affect
drug-seeking behavior (KIRALY et al., 2016).
3.4. Gut microbiota alters the expression of DA receptors
Gut microbiota can also affect the brain’s reward functions, such as
eating, drinking, and addiction, through their effects on dopamine re-
ceptors (DRs) (Fig. 1B). When examining a model of compulsive alcohol
seeking in the dorsal striatum, it was found that the vulnerable group
exhibited significantly greater D1R expression in the dorsal striatum
compared to D2R expression. Besides, D2R mRNA expression in the
striatal is positively correlated with a low abundance of Firmicute bac-
teria, whereas D1R mRNA expression in the striatum is negatively
correlated to the genera Veillonell and Gemella, both of which belong to
the family Ruminococcaceae (JADHAV et al., 2018). AGUSTí et al. (2021)
demonstrated the potential of Bifidobacterium and Bacteroides uniformis
CECT 7771 in modulating neurotransmitter levels and receptor expres-
sion in the nucleus accumbens, prefrontal cortex, and small intestine of
mice
and
rats
with
food
addiction.
Specifically,
Bifidobacterium
increased DA, 5-HT, and noradrenaline levels in the nucleus accumbens,
while restoring D1R and D2R expression in both the prefrontal cortex
and small intestine in mice subjected to intermittent fasting. Further-
more, Bacteroides uniformis CECT 7771 treatment restored D1R-positive
cells throughout the prefrontal cortex and D1R- and D2R-positive cells
within the small intestine in rats with food addiction (AGUSTí et al.,
2021).
S. Qu et al.
Microbiological Research 287 (2024) 127858
6
3.5. Gut microbiota influences by DA metabolism
These DA metabolic pathways influenced by micro-organisms can
also influence micro-organisms on their own reciprocally. Altered DA
signaling has been associated with ASD, recent work suggests that rare
variants of the SLC6A3 gene encoding the DAT identified in individuals
with ASD result in structural and functional changes to the DAT
(DICARLO et al., 2019). Impaired DA signaling due to changes in DAT
structure and function has also been found in animal models of ASD.
Mice with mutant DAT showed autism-like phenotypes and impaired DA
signaling, accompanied by several metabolic and gastrointestinal
changes, such as less Fusobacterium in the digestive tract (DICARLO
et al., 2021).
The MitoPark mouse model, generated through the cre/lox system by
selectively removing mitochondrial transcription factor A from DAT-
positive neurons, results in reduced DA production and a transient in-
crease in Prevotella levels (GHAISAS et al., 2019). Thus, DA metabolic
pathways can also influence microorganisms, highlighting the bidirec-
tional relationship between the gut microbiota and host DA metabolism.
4. Gut microbiota modulates glutamate and GABA
Glutamate
and
GABA
are
essential
neurotransmitters
in
the
mammalian CNS, with glutamate acting as the primary excitatory and
GABA as the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter. These neurotrans-
mitters play crucial roles in various neuropsychiatric diseases. In the GI
system, GABA also functions as a neurotransmitter, with high-affinity
uptake demonstrated in approximately 5–8 % of the total number of
myenteric neurons, indicating their GABAergic nature. Additionally,
GABA is synthesized, stored, and secreted as an endocrine by mucosal
endocrine cells, regulating GI motility, digestive secretory activity, and
immune cell activity associated with intestinal inflammation. These
findings suggest that GABA is a key player in gut-brain communication,
and its modulation could have implications for the treatment of various
gastrointestinal and neuropsychiatric diseases (AUTERI et al., 2015).
In the CNS, GABA synthesis occurs through two main pathways: the
GABA shunt branch and the polyamine degradation pathway (Fig. 1C).
The primary pathway for GABA production and metabolism is the GABA
shunt branch, where glutamate is catalyzed by GAD to undergo an
irreversible decarboxylation reaction at the α-position, resulting in the
production of GABA. Subsequently, GABA reacts with pyruvate and
α-ketoglutarate to form succinate semialdehyde, which is then oxida-
tively dehydrogenated by succinate semialdehyde dehydrogenase to
form succinate. Finally, succinate enters the tricarboxylic acid cycle. The
polyamine degradation pathway is an alternative source of GABA, which
converts polyamine degradation products to GABA. Putrescine is typi-
cally used as the central substance of polyamine biological metabolism.
The polyamine degradation pathway and aldehyde dehydrogenase
dehydrogenate GABA, which then joins the GABA branch and partici-
pates in the TCA cycle metabolism.
Although the specific synthesis process is consistent with the GABA
branch in the gut and brain, the efficiency of GABA synthesis is lower in
the gastrointestinal system compared to the CNS. Gastrointestinal cells
take up glutamate through a specific transporter, where L-glutamate
undergoes irreversible decarboxylation in the cell, consuming a mole-
cule of intracellular proton to generate GABA. Subsequently, GABA is
excreted by the GABA anti-transporter (MA et al., 2012). While the BBB
is impermeable to GABA and glutamate, oral administration of GABA
still affects the function of neuronal cells in the brain. In this case,
GABA-activated enterocytes induce exocytosis to activate neuronal cells
(INOTSUKA et al., 2021). Glutamate and GABA are significant neuro-
modulators, and their metabolism is strongly influenced by the gut
microbiota.
4.1. Gut microbiota modulates glutamate and GABA levels
Many bacterial species have been found to express genes that are
involved in the production, metabolism, and transport of glutamate and
GABA (Fig. 1C ab). These bacteria can produce, utilize, and transport
glutamate and GABA, as well as reuptake glutamate and efflux GABA
(Table 1). The glutamate/GABA antiporter system, which includes
proteins such as GadC and GadT, is essential for bacterial adaptation to
acidic conditions and stress, facilitating the reuptake of glutamate and
the export of GABA. While most GABA is exported by this antiporter
system, it can also be further metabolized by the GABA shunt pathway,
providing an important source of nitrogen for bacteria. The first step in
this pathway is catalyzed by GABA-AT, which converts GABA into
glutamate.
Some organisms, such as Escherichia coli, can utilize GABA as their
sole source of carbon and nitrogen, and under acidic conditions,
Escherichia coli can transport glutamate and GABA by GadC. Besides,
Bacillus subtilis lacks genes encoding GAD, which is necessary for the
production of GABA from putrescine, but it can import extracellular
GABA using a protein with sequence similarity to the GABA permease in
Escherichia coli (FERSON et al., 1996).
4.2. Gut microbiota modulates circulating glutamate/GABA levels
The microbiota appeared to affect circulating glutamate/GABA
levels (Fig. 1C c). Depression may be induced by altering glutamate-
glutamine-GABA cycles in the hippocampus, cerebellum, and striatum
(XU et al., 2020). Glutamate is an important precursor of GABA and a
decrease in its concentration in the anterior cingulate cortex and pre-
frontal cortex has been shown to be associated with MDD. Additionally,
excessive release of glutamate and chronic activation of glutamate re-
ceptors also can lead to excitotoxicity, resulting in neuronal necrosis,
apoptosis, and death. Recent studies have shown that the administration
of Lactobacillus rhamnosus JB-1 to healthy mice for 2 and 4 weeks can
increase glutamine, glutamate, and GABA levels in the CNS, showing an
anxiolytic effect (JANIK et al., 2016). And L. lactis NCDO2118 delivers
GABA into the gastrointestinal tract due to its GAD activity (LAROUTE
et al., 2022). Furthermore, Bifidobacterium adolescentis has been identi-
fied as a key member of the human gut microbiota in the production of
GABA in anxiety and depression through the upregulation of Gad genes
in both human and animal models (DURANTI et al., 2020; ROYO et al.,
2023).
A meta-analysis of 24 studies of gut microbiota in MDD patients
found a decrease in Faecalibacterium and Ruminococcus in MDD patients
and these bacteria are associated with glutamate and GABA metabolism
(SANADA et al., 2020). Electroacupuncture significantly improves
behavioral tests and alters the composition of the gut microbiota by
significantly increasing the SCFAs producers, such as Rumex, Fasciola,
and Acromansiacae, and increasing the levels of GABA, L-glutamine, and
glutamate/glutamine in the hippocampus. It is considered an emerging
antidepressant therapy that affects vagal nerve impulses (ZHOU et al.,
2022). An open-label study suggests that Clostridium butyricum MIYAIRI
588 in combination with antidepressants is effective and well-tolerated
in the treatment of treatment-resistant MDD. The presumed mechanism
is that Clostridium butyricum ameliorates MDD and may be related to
neuroprotection (neurogenesis, antioxidation, and antiglutamate exci-
totoxicity) (MIYAOKA et al., 2018).
Mounting preclinical and clinical evidence highlights the impact of
gut microbiota alterations on the onset of visceral hypersensitivity, a
prominent symptom in individuals with IBS that manifests as diffuse and
poorly localized chronic abdominal pain. This phenomenon may be
attributed to the sustained activation of glutamatergic pathways (CHEN
et al., 2017). Notably, commensal Bifidobacterium dentium produces
GABA by enzymatic decarboxylation of glutamate via GadB, and oral
administration of this Bifidobacterium can modulate the activity of sen-
sory neurons in the rat of visceral hypersensitivity which indicates its
S. Qu et al.
Microbiological Research 287 (2024) 127858
7
potential in treatment (POKUSAEVA et al., 2017).
4.3. Gut microbiota influences the expression of glutamate/GABA
receptors
In addition, the gut microbiota affects the expression of central
glutamate and GABA receptors in the host (Fig. 1C d). Transplanting
fecal microbiota from alcoholism patients to mice induces anxiety and
depression behaviors, while also decreasing the levels of mGluR1
(metabotropic glutamate receptor 1)/ PKCε(protein kinase C) in the
medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens (ZHAO et al., 2020). It
has been observed that rats administered fructo-oligosaccharide or
galactooligosaccharides prebiotics showed increased levels of BDNF in
their hippocampi and N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor (NR)1 subunit
expression, as well as increased hippocampal NR2A subunits, frontal
cortex NR1, and d-serine, which impart significant anxiolytic effects
(SAVIGNAC et al., 2013). Recent studies also show that L. rhamnosus
HN001 reduced GABAA subunit expression in the amygdala and hip-
pocampus in rats (DALZIEL et al., 2023). For GABA receptors, reduced
expression of the α5 and δ subunits of the GABAA receptor in the hip-
pocampus of rats exposed to early gut microbiota disorders (an increase
in Enterococcus and E. coli counts and a decrease in Lactobacillus) leads
to upstream control of the limbic system (LIANG et al., 2017). Moderate
administration of probiotics (Lactobacillus rhamnosus and Bifidobacte-
rium longum) increased the expression of the δ subunit in the DG region
of the hippocampus and the α5 subunit in the CA3 region of the hip-
pocampus (LIANG et al., 2017). However, receptor expression in the
brain doesn’t always increase. It was found that administration of
Lactobacillus rhamnosus (JB-1) to mice resulted in region-dependent al-
terations in mRNA of GABAB receptors in the brain, with increased
expression in cortical regions and decreased expression in hippocampal
regions compared to control-fed mice, ultimately showing a decrease in
depression-related behaviors in mice (BRAVO et al., 2011). As a result,
Lactobacillus strains regulate emotional behavior and expression of
GABA receptors in mice when ingested.
4.4. Gut microbiota influenced by glutamate/GABA metabolism
Besides, these glutamate/GABA metabolic pathways influenced by
microorganisms can also influence microorganisms on their own in turn.
In the metabotropic glutamate receptor knock-out mice, there is a
decrease in the abundance of the Erysipelotrichaceae family and Allo-
baculum genus, which may be helpful as a preclinical model of depres-
sion and schizophrenia (GUBERT et al., 2020). Mice that are deficient in
IL-10 show a 100 % penetrance of spontaneous and aggressive
Crohn’s-like disease, which may be linked to reduced expression of
Foxo3a, a signaling molecule that represses glutaminase transcription. In
Foxo3a−/−IL-10−/−
mice,
higher
serum
glutamate
levels
were
observed, along with a greater abundance of Actinobacteria and Proteo-
bacteria, including increased Enterobacteriaceae, compared to IL-10−/−
mice (HAJJAR et al., 2022).
5. Structural foundation for the gut-brain signaling
While
gut
microbiota
can
impact neurotransmitter
synthesis,
degradation, and gut-brain signaling through various mechanisms, it is
important to note that these neurotransmitters cannot directly cross the
BBB. Instead, a key structural foundation for gut-brain signaling is
composed of various intestinal receptors and the enteric nerve-vagus
nerve system, which mediate the effects of nutrients, gut-derived neu-
rotransmitters, hormones, and mechanical pressure, among others. The
ENS-VNS-CNS network thus represents a crucial structural foundation
for modulating the gut microbiota’s effects on neurotransmitters and
gut-brain communication (Fig. 1D).
5.1. Enteric nerve-vagal nerve system
The gastrointestinal tract is innervated by two types of nerves: the
extrinsic autonomic nervous system (ANS) and the intrinsic ENS (FUR-
NESS, 2012). Extrinsic sympathetic and parasympathetic nerve fibers
penetrate the entire intestinal wall and form complex neural networks
with intrinsic enteric nervous and Enteric Glial Cells (EGCs), which
innervate gastrointestinal epithelial and immune cells. The ENS net-
works present in the GI tract, including myenteric and submucosal
plexuses, as well as the interstitial cells of Cajal, enable a significant
degree of autonomy over GI functions, such as the regulation of
gastrointestinal motility and secretion, respectively. These two plexuses
are made up of intrinsic neurons that receive input from the intestine’s
external sympathetic and parasympathetic innervation (Fig. 1E).
Accumulating evidence supports the significant impact of gut
microbiota on physiological processes and homeostasis of brain func-
tions (SHERWIN et al., 2019) via the vagal nerve. In normal conditions,
the gut microbiota is not capable of directly activating vagal nerve cells,
unless there is impaired intestinal permeability, such as inflammation or
stress. Indirect activation of vagal nerve cells by luminal bacteria occurs
through the stimulation and release of neuroactive mediators by endo-
crine cells or the gut-associated lymphoid tissue (Fig. 1F). Studies have
shown that vagotomy, a surgical procedure that involves cutting the
vagus nerve, can lead to a decrease in the number of immature neurons
and activation of microglia in the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus
(CRYAN et al., 2019).
In rodent models, activating the vagal nerve increases neurogenesis
in the adult hippocampus and modulates neurotransmitter release in
brain regions related to anxiety and depression (CARPENTER et al.,
2004). Administering pathogenic bacteria, such as Campylobacter jejuni,
orally to healthy mice induces anxiety-like behaviors and activates the
cFos gene in various brain regions through the vagal nerve (GOEHLER
et al., 2008). Oral administration of SSRIs (MCVEY NEUFELD et al.,
2019) or psychoactive bacteria like Lactobacillus rhamnosus (BHARWANI
et al., 2020) and Lactobacillus reuteri (WANG et al., 2020) can increase
vagal activity and exert antidepressant effects. VNS was approved for the
treatment of treatment-resistant depression two decades ago. In PD,
early alpha-synuclein pathology is often found in structures that provide
parasympathetic innervation to the gut. As a result, the vagal nerve may
serve as a pathway for the spread of alpha-synuclein–related neuropa-
thology from the ENS to the CNS (SCHEPERJANS et al., 2015). VNS
increases the activation of noradrenergic neurons in the locus coeruleu
(HULSEY et al., 2017) and specifically activates the vagus sensory
ganglion, which projects to the NTS and other targets dopamine neurons
in the Substantia nigra (HAN et al., 2018), ultimately activating dopa-
minergic neurons in the ventral tegmental area and influencing behav-
iors dependent on dopamine signaling (HAN et al., 2018; FERNANDES
et al., 2020)(Fig. 1H). This evidence demonstrates that the ENS and
afferent ANS pathways provide a structural foundation for microbiota to
locally influence intestinal function and regulate CNS function through
specific neuronal circuitries, thus establishing bidirectional communi-
cation between the gut and the brain (Fig. 1G).
5.2. Intestinal neurotransmitter receptors
As the keys and doors, activation of the neurotransmitter’s receptors
expressed in ENS stimulates ddifferent neuronal circuitries by different
intestinal neurotransmitters, thus different functions of ENS and CNS, as
well as the signaling between ENS-CNS.
5.2.1. 5-HT receptors
The 5-HT transporter reuptakes 5-HT into 5-HTergic neurons and
inactivates it by binding to 5-HT receptors. Seven types or families of 5-
HT receptors and multiple subtypes have been identified, including 5-
HT1, 5-HT2, 5-HT3, 5-HT4, 5-HT5, 5-HT6, and 5-HT7 receptors. Several of
these receptors expressed in the CNS are also expressed in the ENS,
S. Qu et al.
Microbiological Research 287 (2024) 127858
8
playing different roles in the regulation of intestinal motility and
secretion (either inhibitory or excitatory). In the ENS, 5-HT binds to 5-
HT1P and 5-HT3 receptors to increase the excitability of vagal afferent
fibers. 5-HT3 and 5-HT4 receptors seem to be related to vasodilatory
responses that are activated by mucosal stimulation. 5-HT binds to 5-
HT2A, 5-HT3, 5-HT4, and 5-HT7 receptors to regulate smooth muscle
contraction and diastole, and it also binds to 5-HT3, 5-HT4, and 5-HT1P
receptors to regulate neurogenic secretory responses (MAWE and
HOFFMAN, 2013). Gut-derived 5-HT could activate nearby 5-HT re-
ceptors in afferent tracts thus activating the vagal nerve, and further
regulating the release of 5-HT in the brain (KIM and CAMILLERI, 2000).
5.2.2. DA receptors
There are two main classes of G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs)
that regulate the physiological effects of DA: D1R and D2R (BEAULIEU
and GAINETDINOV, 2011). DR of the D1R class (D1R and D5R) are
usually linked to Gs/olf, stimulate cAMP production through adenylate
cyclase, and are exclusively present on DR cells (postsynaptic neurons).
D2R and D3R express postsynaptically on DA target cells and dopami-
nergic neurons, instead of D1R. D2R class (D2R, D3R, and D4R) is coupled
to Gi/o, thereby inducing inhibition of AC and negative regulation of
cAMP. D1R -D5R are distributed in both the CNS and the peripheral
nervous system (Fig. 1C).
In ENS, dopaminergic neurons make up 14 %-20 % of all enteric
neurons in the upper GI tract, with this proportion decreasing to 1 %-
6 % in the lower small and large intestines due to the distribution of the
GI gradient. These dopaminergic neurons express TH and lack dopamine
beta-hydroxylase (ANLAUF et al., 2003). This Anatomical muscle and
interosseous plexuses contain transcripts encoding D1R to D3R and D5R,
whereas mucosa contains D1R and D3R to D5R (LI et al., 2006). Within
the gut, D5Rs form a complex with CCR9 to provide surface receptors for
colon tropism to effector CD4 T cells in inflammatory bowel disease. In
the ENS, DAT is linked to the motor response that involves the partici-
pation of D1Rs. When DAT levels are reduced, it can lead to morpho-
logical abnormalities in the enteric glial network (CERANTOLA et al.,
2021).
5.2.3. Glutamate and GABA receptors
Glutamate acts as an excitatory neurotransmitter, primarily through
its action on ionotropic and metabotropic glutamate receptors. These
receptors are involved in motor and secretory reflex responses, as well as
in the perception of visceral pain. Glutamate receptors also regulate
pathways that transmit sensory information to the CNS and control in-
puts from the CNS to the gastrointestinal tract (FILPA et al., 2016).
GABA, on the other hand, acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter
through its ionotropic GABAA, GABAC receptors, as well as metabotropic
GABAB receptors. In the ENS, activation of ionotropic GABAA and
GABAC receptors typically leads to the release of neurotransmitters,
including acetylcholine and non-adrenergic, non-cholinergic neuro-
transmitters, from enteric neurons. This release can result in either
contractile or relaxant responses in the GI smooth muscle. Conversely,
activation of GABAB receptors can reduce the release of acetylcholine by
inhibiting voltage-dependent calcium channels in enteric neuron
(AUTERI et al., 2015).
5.3. Neuropod cells, the foundation of gut-brain sensory transduction
The intestinal villous epithelial wall, which directly senses the food
and gut microbiota, converts external stimuli into electrochemical sig-
nals and triggers a signaling cascade from the gut to the brain within a
millisecond (KAELBERER et al., 2020). In the intestinal epithelial cells,
the neuropod cell, also called the EECs (KAELBERER et al., 2020) syn-
apses with vagal neurons and EGCs, providing the entry point for sen-
sory signal transduction from the intestinal milieu to the brain through
fast neurotransmission (KAELBERER et al., 2018). These signals include
luminal nutrients (such as glucose, amino acid, peptides, protein
hydrolysates, calcium, and long-chain fatty acids), bacterial by-products
(such as SCFAs), gut hormones, and neurotransmitters (Fig. 1F).
Several GPCRs are found in the intestinal epithelia, particularly on
the apical membrane of neuropod cells. These receptors are believed to
mediate specific signals, with different populations of vagal afferents
responding to them. Studies have shown that nutritive sugar, but not
non-caloric sweeteners, can stimulate glutamatergic neurotransmission
of neuropod cells to trigger vagal firing (BUCHANAN et al., 2022). Free
fatty acid receptors FFAR1 and FFAR4, which respond to long-chain fatty
acids, are linked to the elevation of gut hormones after fat ingestion.
FFAR2 and FFAR3, receptors for SCFAs produced by microbial fermen-
tation of dietary fiber, can stimulate the release of GLP-1 and peptide YY,
contributing to appetite control and hormone release related to food
intake. The tryptophan metabolite kynurenic acid can activate GPR35
on the lumen side of neuropod cells. GPR142, an amino acid receptor
expressed in gastrointestinal neuropod cells, is activated by L-phenyl-
alanine and L-tryptophan. The ionotropic 5-HT3A receptor, expressed by
vagal nerves in the small intestine’s villi, is known to be activated by
5-HT (LUND et al., 2018). When GPR142 is stimulated by tryptophan, it
triggers the release of 5-HT, which is transmitted to the CNS through the
vagal nerve (RUDENKO et al., 2019). L-Trp also stimulates insulin
secretion via GPR142 to improve glucose metabolism (LIN et al., 2016).
5.4. Mechanical receptor in cells of the wall of the intestine
There are specialized receptors in the gut wall that respond to me-
chanical and chemical signals, such as stretch, tension, and capsaicin.
These receptors, called purinoceptor 2X (P2X) receptors, are channels
that allow ions like Na+, K+, and Ca2+ to pass through when activated.
This results in an increase in intracellular Ca2+ and depolarization
waves, leading to signal transmission (KHAKH and NORTH, 2012).
Studies have shown that P2X(2) and P2X(3) receptor subunits are
involved in the mechanosensitivity of small intestinal afferents in mice
(RONG et al., 2009). When extracellular adenosine triphosphate acti-
vates P2X receptors on cell membranes, it triggers various intracellular
signaling pathways and inflammatory reactions, causing damage to the
nervous system and inducing pain (ZHANG et al., 2020).
Capsaicin activates transient receptor potential vanilloid 1 (TRPV1)
(YANG and ZHENG, 2017), a receptor associated with peripheral neu-
ropathy and chronic inflammatory pain (AGHAZADEH TABRIZI et al.,
2017). TRPV1 plays a key role in toxic heat perception and is located at
sensory nerve endings. Activation of TRPV1 leads to membrane depo-
larization and electrical transmission to the spinal cord and brain,
resulting in pain sensation. Modulating TRPV1 channels may have
therapeutic applications for treating inflammatory and neuropathic
pain. Capsaicin also activates GLP-1R neurons involved in mechanical
distension of the stomach and intestine, while only a few GPR65 neurons
are activated. GPR65 is associated with homeostatic responses to
ingested nutrients.
Interestingly, there are cross-talks between mechanical signals and
neurotransmitter signals (Fig. 1E). The mechanosensitive ion channel
Piezo2 is specifically expressed on the luminal side of ECCs. In response
to mechanical pressure, such as stretching and poking the mucosa,
Piezo2 creates an ionic current, which releases 5-HT into the body. It
explains, in part, why mechanical forces trigger 5-HT release (ALCAINO
et al., 2018a). The Piezo2-expressing neurons project directly to the
gastrointestinal tract and vagus innervation layer, forming intra-
ganglionic varicose endings (WOLFSON et al., 2023). Pizeo2 combines
the perception of the intestinal environment, the action of mechanical
forces, and the secretion of 5-HT. The short-lived mechanical stimula-
tion of food, together with the longer-acting endocrine, can regulate the
orderly movement of the intestine (SERVIN-VENCES et al., 2023;
ALCAINO et al., 2018b).
Piezo2 is critical to ECC mechanosensitivity and 5-HT signaling that
induces downstream physiological effects. The co-localization of
cannabinoid 1 and TRPV1 receptors indicates cross-talk between these
S. Qu et al.
Microbiological Research 287 (2024) 127858
9
receptors, and a subclass of endocannabinoids (eCBs) also acts through
TRPV1. Dopamine derivatives like N-arachidonoyl-dopamine are ago-
nists of TRPV1, while 5-HT derivatives like N-arachidonoyl-5-hydroxy-
tryptamine act as antagonists of TRPV1 (ARNOLD et al., 2021).
Targeting the eCBs-TRPV1 axis has profound anti-nociceptive effects
and anti-inflammatory activity, making it a promising avenue for the
development of novel non-opioid pain therapeutics.
6. Prospectus
Although the bidirectional interactions between microbiota-gut-
brain are comprehensive and still a black box, accumulating evidence
supports that gut microbiotas can modulate neurotransmitters and the
signaling between the gut and brain. Gut microbiota may influence
neurotransmitter synthesis and metabolism both in vitro and in vivo
within the gut. They can regulate the synthesis and metabolism of
neurotransmitters in the gut and brain of the host, or indirectly stimulate
the ENS-VNS activity, thus modulating signaling from the gut to the
brain and ultimately affecting neurotransmitter levels in the brain. It is
still necessary to further clarify the effect of gut microbiotas on neuro-
transmitters along the Microbiota-Gut-Brain axis and further identify the
underlying mechanisms, thus exploring the novel therapeutic ap-
proaches
for
brain
disorders
targeting
the
regulation
of
neurotransmitters.
